Placement groups.

By default, AWS spreads your instances across hardware to minimize the chance that one failure takes out several of them. Placement groups let you override that default in one of three ways.

A cluster placement group packs instances onto the same rack in a single zone, giving you the lowest possible latency and the highest bandwidth between them; the trade is that a rack-level failure can take the whole group down, so it's for tightly coupled high-performance computing and big-data jobs with heavy shuffle.

A spread placement group does the opposite, putting each instance on a different rack with distinct power and hardware, capped at seven instances per zone; it's for small fleets of critical instances where you can't tolerate two failing together, like a primary and standby database pair.

A partition placement group groups instances into partitions that share no hardware between them, and instances can read their partition number, which suits large, topology-aware distributed systems like Cassandra, Kafka, and the hadoop file system.

So: cluster for latency, spread for isolation, partition for big topology-aware systems.
